{
  "answer": "**The couplet you're referring to is the opening sher (couplet) of the ghazal itself, which is named after it.**[^1][^2][^3]\n\n**Original (Urdu):**  \nدل ہی تو ہے نہ سنگ_و_خشت درد سے بھر نہ آئے کیوں  \nروئیں_گے ہم ہزار بار کوئی ہمیں ستائے کیوں  \n\n**Transliteration:**  \nDil hi to hai na sang-o-khisht, dard se bhar na aaye kyun?  \nRoyenge hum hazaar baar, koi hamein sataaye kyun?  \n\n**Translation:**  \nIt is a heart, not stone and brick, that fills with pain;  \nWe'll weep a thousand times—why should a soul be slain?  \n\nThis directly contrasts the heart (*dil*) with stone (*sang*) and brick (*khisht*), emphasizing its vulnerability to sorrow.\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/33-dil-hi-to-hai-na-sang-o-khisht-dard-se-bhar-na-aay/translation/#p-d9d50d).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/33-dil-hi-to-hai-na-sang-o-khisht-dard-se-bhar-na-aay/transliteration/#p-4585fc).\n\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/33-dil-hi-to-hai-na-sang-o-khisht-dard-se-bhar-na-aay/original/#p-679dc6).",
